OrganizationFormalName: USGS New Mexico Water Science Center
National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Bubbling Spring discharges from the lower DeChelly Sandstone in Spring Canyon, a tributary to Canyon de Chelly in Canyon de Chelly National Monument. The spring supports a small riparian community and water samples were collected in a small channel about 30 feet from the spring orifice.  Water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Chinle Creek at Chinle, AZ is a USGS streamflow gaging station near the Canyon de Chelly National Monument boundary. Chinle Creek flows intermittently in a broad, sandbedded channel. Water samples were collected at the gaging station.  Intermittent water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.  Water is important for subsistence agriculture now practiced in the canyon. Agricultural and industrial activities occur currently or have occurred historically in the Chinle Wash watershed. Erosion is a concern in the Canyon de Chelly and erosion can degrade waterquality.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Chinle Wash below White House Ruins
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Chinle Wash primarily flows east to west through Canyon de Chelly. White House Ruins is located on canyon walls about 500 feet north of the wash. The wash flows intermittently in this section of Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Water samples were collected about 1,00 feet downstream of the ruins along a meandering stretch of river.  Intermittent water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.  Water is important for subsistence agriculture now practiced in the canyon. Agricultural and industrial activities occur currently or have occurred historically in the Chinle Wash watershed. Erosion is a concern in the Canyon de Chelly and erosion can degrade waterquality.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Many Cherry Spring discharges from the base of Shinarump Formation where it is exposed in a rock wall near the head of Many Cherry Canyon in Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Water samples were collected from a pool near the base of the rock wall.  Water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Pine Tree Canyon Tinaja is a large pool that is filled by water discharging from horizontal seams in the DeChelly Sandstone. The pool provides habitat for amphibians and aquatic macroinvertebrates. Water samples were pumped directly from the pool.  Water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Tsaile Creek at Bare Rock Trail Crossing
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Tsaile Creek flows east to west through Canyon del Muerto along a sand and bedrock channel.  The creek is intermittent in this section of Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Water samples were collected where Bare Rock Trail crosses Tsaile Creek.  Intermittent water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.  Water is important for subsistence agriculture now practiced in the canyon. Agricultural and industrial activities occur currently or have occurred historically in the Tsaile Creek watershed. Erosion is a concern in the Canyon de Chelly and erosion can degrade waterquality.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Tsaile Creek flows through Canyon del Muerto in Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Flow in the creek is dependent on releases from Tsaile Lake and is perennial in the reach immediately downstream of the dam. Water was sampled at the weir on Tsaile Creek, located about 2,000 ft below the dam.  Perennial water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.  Water is important for subsistence agriculture now practiced in the canyon. Agricultural and industrial activities occur currently or have occurred historically in the Tsaile Creek watershed. Erosion is a concern in the Canyon de Chelly and erosion can degrade waterquality.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Tsaile Lake is a small reservoir situated on Navajo Nation Tribal lands and on Canyon de Chelly National Monument. The reservoir is fed by Tsaile Creek and is formed by a earthen dam. Tsaile Lake is used for recreation, wildlife, and livestock.  Water was sampled from the west bank of the lake along the road on the dam.  Perennial water sources in Canyon de Chelly National Monument are important features for flora, fauna, past cultures, and those presently living in the canyon.  Water is important for subsistence agriculture now practiced in the canyon.  Agricultural and industrial activities occur currently or have occurred historically in the Tsaile Creek watershed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: NPS Canyon de Chelly Well No. 2
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: NPS Canyon de Chelly Well No. 2 is located near the Thunderbird Lodge in Canyon de Chelly National Monument.  Water samples were collected from the well faucet before any filtering or treatment of the well water.  The well is 110 feet deep and recent water level information could be obtained.  This is the water supply well for Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Water samples provide information about the waterquality.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Kokopelli Spring is a small springfed pool situated in the Chinle Formation at Petrified Forest National Park.  Water samples were collected by pumping water directly from the pool.  Wildlife use this spring as a water source and water samples provide information about the waterquality.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: The Puerco River primarily flows west to east, is intermittent, and runs through the narrow midsection of Petrified Forest National Park.  Only about 1.7 miles of the river are within park boundaries.  Water samples were collected about 1,500 feet upstream of the bridge on Petrified Forest Highway.  The Puerco River supports a riparian plant community, providing important habitat for wildlife. Agricultural and industrial activities occur currently or have occurred historically in the Puerco River watershed.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationDescriptionText: Puerco Well No 2 is located about 200 feet north of the Puerco River in Petrified Forest National Park. The well is developed in a shallow alluvial aquifer and was intended to provide domestic water to the park, but is not currently used for this purpose.  This well is a backup drinking water supply for Petrified Forest National Park. Water samples provide information about the waterquality.

OrganizationFormalName: National Park Service Water Resources Division
MonitoringLocationName: Puerco River at Highway Bridge in Petrified Forest N.P.
